To evaluate \(\displaystyle \log_{5}(100)\) by the change-of-base formula, write it in terms of common (or natural) logarithms. For example, using base-10 logs,

\[
\log_{5}(100)
=\frac{\log_{10}(100)}{\log_{10}(5)}
=\frac{2}{\log_{10}(5)}
\approx \frac{2}{0.69897}
\approx 2.86135.
\]

Or equivalently with natural logs,

\[
\log_{5}(100)
=\frac{\ln(100)}{\ln(5)}
=\frac{2\ln(10)}{\ln(5)}
\approx \frac{2\cdot2.302585}{1.609437}
\approx 2.86135.
\]
